Psychoanalysis has the longest tradition in the psychotherapeutic treatment of cancer patients. The need for modifications in the psychotherapeutic setting and process in working with organically ill patients was recognized early. The contributions of Freyberger and Speidel (1976) were essential for the development of the "supportive therapy". The advantages of this psychodynamic supportive intervention compared with the wide-spread group support programs for cancer patients are explained.  
